\section{Running and plotting the simulations: starting, ending, and
  examples}\label{simul}

\subsection{Starting and ending}
\label{sec:starting-ending}


After you have decided the specifics of the fitness effects and the model,
you need to decide:

\begin{itemize}
\item Where will you start your simulation from. This involves deciding
  the initial population size (argument \texttt{initSize}) and, possibly,
  the genotype of the initial population; the later is covered in section
  \qref{initmut}.

\item When will you stop it: how long to run it, and whether or not to
  require simulations to reach cancer (under some definition of what it
  means to reach cancer). This is covered in \qref{endsimul}.
\end{itemize}


\subsection{Can I start the simulation from a specific mutant?}\label{initmut}

You bet. In v.1 you can only give the initial mutant as one with a single
mutated gene. In version 2, however, you can specify the genotype for the
initial mutant with the same flexibility as in
\Rfunction{evalGenotype}. Here we show a couple of examples (we use the
representation of the parent-child relationships ---discussed in section
\ref{phylog}--- of the clones so that you can see which clones appear, and
from which).

%% o3init <- allFitnessEffects(orderEffects = c(
%%                             "M > D > F" = 0.99,
%%                             "D > M > F" = 0.2,
%%                             "D > M"     = 0.1,
%%                             "M > D"     = 0.9),
%%                         noIntGenes = c("u" = 0.01, 
%%                                        "v" = 0.01,
%%                                        "w" = 0.001,
%%                                        "x" = 0.0001,
%%                                        "y" = -0.0001,
%%                                        "z" = -0.001),
%%                         geneToModule =
%%                             c("Root" = "Root",
%%                               "M" = "m",
%%                               "F" = "f",
%%                               "D" = "d") )
<<fig.height=6>>=

o3init <- allFitnessEffects(orderEffects = c(
                            "M > D > F" = 0.99,
                            "D > M > F" = 0.2,
                            "D > M"     = 0.1,
                            "M > D"     = 0.9),
                        noIntGenes = c("u" = 0.01, 
                                       "v" = 0.01,
                                       "w" = 0.001,
                                       "x" = 0.0001,
                                       "y" = -0.0001,
                                       "z" = -0.001),
                        geneToModule =
                            c("M" = "m",
                              "F" = "f",
                              "D" = "d") )

oneI <- oncoSimulIndiv(o3init, model = "McFL",
                       mu = 5e-5, finalTime = 500,
                       detectionDrivers = 3,
                       onlyCancer = FALSE,
                       initSize = 1000,
                       keepPhylog = TRUE,
                       initMutant = c("m > u > d")
                       )
plotClonePhylog(oneI, N = 0)


## 
## Note we also disable the stopping stochastically
## as a function of size to allow the pop to grow
## large and generate may different clones.
ospI <- oncoSimulPop(4, 
                    o3init, model = "Exp",
                    mu = 5e-5, finalTime = 500,
                    detectionDrivers = 3,
                    onlyCancer = TRUE,
                    initSize = 10,
                    keepPhylog = TRUE,
                    initMutant = c("d > m > z"),
                    mc.cores = 2
                    )

op <- par(mar = rep(0, 4), mfrow = c(2, 2))
plotClonePhylog(ospI[[1]])
plotClonePhylog(ospI[[2]])
plotClonePhylog(ospI[[3]])
plotClonePhylog(ospI[[4]])
par(op)


ossI <- oncoSimulSample(4, 
                        o3init, model = "Exp",
                        mu = 5e-5, finalTime = 500,
                        detectionDrivers = 2,
                        onlyCancer = TRUE,
                        initSize = 10,
                        initMutant = c("z > d"),
                        thresholdWhole = 1 ## check presence of initMutant
                    )

## No phylogeny is kept with oncoSimulSample, but look at the 
## OcurringDrivers and the sample

ossI$popSample
ossI$popSummary[, "OccurringDrivers", drop = FALSE]


@ 

\subsection{Ending the simulations}
\label{endsimul}

OncoSimulR provides very flexible ways to decide when to stop a
simulation. Here we focus on a single simulation; see further options with
multiple simulations in \qref{sample}.


\begin{description}
\item[\texttt{onlyCancer = TRUE}] A simulation will be repeated until any
  one of the ``reach cancer'' conditions is met, if this happens before
  the simulation reaches \texttt{finalTime}\footnote{Of course, the
    ``reach cancer'' idea and the \texttt{onlyCancer} argument are generic
    names; this could have been labeled ``reach whatever interests
    me''.}. These conditions are:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item Total population size becomes larger than \texttt{detectionSize}.
  \item The number of drivers in any one genotype or clone becomes equal
    to, or larger than, \texttt{detectionDrivers}; note that this allows you
    to stop the simulation as soon as a \textbf{specific genotype} is
    found, by using exactly and only the genes that make that genotype as
    the drivers.
  \item The tumor is detected according to a stochastic detection
    mechanism, where the probability of ``detecting the tumor'' increases
    with population size; this is explained below (\qref{detectprob}) and
    is controlled by argument \texttt{detectionProb}.
  \end{itemize}
  
  As we exit as soon as any of the exiting conditions is reached, if you
  only care about one condition, set the other to \texttt{NA}.

\item[\texttt{onlyCancer = FALSE}] A simulation will run only once, and
  will exit as soon as any of the above conditions are met or as soon as
  the total population size becomes zero or we reach \texttt{finalTime}.
\end{description}


As an example of \texttt{onlyCancer = TRUE}, focusing on the first two
mechanisms, suppose you give \texttt{detectionSize = 1e4} and
\texttt{detectionDrivers = 3} (and you have \texttt{detectionProb =
  NA}). A simulation will exit as soon as it reaches a total population
size of $1e4$ or any clone has four drivers, whichever comes first (if any
of these happen before \texttt{finalTime}).

In the \texttt{onlyCancer = TRUE} case, what happens if we reach
\texttt{finalTime} (or the population size becomes zero) before any of the
``reach cancer'' conditions have been fulfilled?  The simulation will be
repeated again, within the following limits:

\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{max.wall.time}: the total wall time we allow an individual
  simulation to run;
\item \texttt{max.num.tries}: the maximum number of times we allow a
  simulation to be repeated to reach cancer;
\item \texttt{max.wall.time.total} and \texttt{max.num.tries.total},
  similar to the above but over a set of simulations in function
  \Rfunction{oncoSimulSample}.
\end{itemize}


Incidentally, we keep track of the number of attempts used (the component
\texttt{other$attemptsUsed$}) before we reach cancer, so you can estimate
(as from a negative binomial sampling) the probability of reaching your
desired end point under different scenarios.


The \texttt{onlyCancer = FALSE} case might be what you want to do when you
examine general population genetics scenarios without focusing on possible
sampling issues. To do this, set \texttt{finalTime} to the value you want
and set \texttt{onlyCancer = FALSE}; in addition, set
\texttt{detectionProb} to ``NA'' and \texttt{detectionDrivers} and
\texttt{detectionSize} to ``NA'' or to huge numbers\footnote{Setting
  \texttt{detectionDrivers} and \texttt{detectionSize} to ``NA'' is in
  fact equivalent to setting them to the largest possible numbers for
  these variables: $2^32 -1$ and $\infty$, respectively.}. In this
scenario you simply collect the simulation output at the end of the run,
regardless of what happened with the population (it became extinct, it did
not reach a large size, it did not accumulate drivers, etc).





